export const story = {"seriesId":"the-wrong-pet-club","storyId":"the-wrong-pet-club","storyKey":"the-wrong-pet-club/the-wrong-pet-club","seriesTitle":"The Wrong Pet Club","seriesDescription":"Maya wanted a running dog. She got Speedy, a three-legged rescue who stops to smell everything. Ben's chameleon won't change colors. Jenna's cat might not exist. Together, they're the Wrong Pet Club—and they're about to find out their pets aren't wrong at all.","title":"The Wrong Pet Club","author":"Andrew","description":"Maya wanted a running dog. She got Speedy, a three-legged rescue who stops to smell everything. Ben's chameleon won't change colors. Jenna's cat might not exist. Together, they're the Wrong Pet Club—and they're about to find out their pets aren't wrong at all.","ageRange":"8-10","genre":"Humor","tags":["funny","pets","friendship","family","dogs","cats"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"The Worst Best Day","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# The Worst Best Day\n\nI had a plan.\n\nThe plan was called \"Maya's Perfect Dog Plan\" and it lived in a spreadsheet on Mom's computer. I'd been adding to it for seven months. There were columns for breed, size, speed, trainability, and \"likelihood to go running with me every single morning.\" I had researched. I had prepared. I had ranked seventeen different dogs from best to worst based on data.\n\nAnd then I went to the shelter and they gave me Speedy.\n\nLet me back up.\n\nThe day started perfectly. Saturday morning, 8:47 AM—a little behind schedule, but acceptable. Mom drove me and my brother Leo to the Greenbrook Animal Shelter, which was hosting an adoption event. I had printed out information on three dogs I wanted to meet. I had backup options. I had questions prepared for the shelter workers.\n\nLeo had a folded-up piece of paper that he wouldn't let me see.\n\n\"It's a map,\" he said.\n\n\"A map of what?\"\n\n\"Things.\"\n\nLeo is six, and his answers are like that. Short. Unhelpful. He's been making maps for months—of what, I don't know. Last week I saw one labeled \"SQUEAKY GATES OF MAPLE STREET (RANKED BY SQUEAKINESS).\" The week before that: \"SNAILS I HAVE MET.\" He draws little symbols and legends and everything. It's weird, but it keeps him busy.\n\nAt the shelter, I walked in with purpose. I knew exactly which kennels to visit. I knew exactly which dogs matched my criteria.\n\nThat's when I saw him.\n\nKennel 14. A lean, athletic mutt with long legs and alert eyes. The card on his cage said ROCKET. Rocket! That was the perfect name. He looked fast. He looked eager. He looked like he wanted to run five miles every morning and then do it again.\n\n\"That one,\" I said to Mom. \"Rocket. He's perfect.\"\n\nThe shelter worker—a tired-looking woman with a ponytail and dog hair on her shirt—checked her clipboard. \"Rocket? Oh, honey. He was adopted about five minutes ago.\"\n\nFive minutes.\n\nI had lost my perfect dog by five minutes because Leo had to stop and look at a weird crack in the parking lot. (He's mapping those too, apparently. \"Cracks That Look Like Animals.\" We were late because of one that \"kind of looked like a duck if you squinted.\")\n\n\"We have other dogs,\" the worker said. \"Actually, we have a special needs placement that would be perfect for a responsible kid like you.\"\n\nI should have said no. I should have stuck to the spreadsheet. But Mom was giving me the look that meant *be polite*, and the worker was already leading us to the back.\n\nThat's where I met Speedy.\n\nSpeedy was lying in her kennel like she'd been waiting for me specifically. She was medium-sized, brown and white, with soft eyes and a tail that wagged slowly when she saw me—and I do mean *slowly*, like she was conserving energy for something more important later.\n\nShe also had three legs.\n\n\"What happened to her leg?\" I asked.\n\n\"She was born this way,\" the worker said. \"Some dogs just are. She gets around fine. She's very sweet. Very calm.\"\n\n\"Calm\" was not on my spreadsheet. \"Calm\" was the opposite of what I wanted. I wanted *energetic*. I wanted *athletic*. I wanted a dog who would keep up with me.\n\n\"Her name is Speedy,\" the worker added.\n\nI looked at the three-legged dog lying completely still in her kennel. \"Is that... a joke?\"\n\n\"The volunteers named her. They have a sense of humor.\"\n\nSpeedy lifted her head, looked at me, and yawned. It was the slowest yawn I'd ever seen. It lasted approximately four seconds. I know because I counted.\n\n\"She's perfect,\" Mom said.\n\n\"She has three legs.\"\n\n\"She has a good heart.\"\n\n\"Hearts aren't on my spreadsheet.\"\n\n\"Maya.\"\n\nAnd that's how I ended up walking out of the shelter with a three-legged dog named Speedy who did not, in any way, live up to her name.\n\n---\n\nOur first walk was a disaster.\n\nI had planned a route: two blocks to the park, one lap around, two blocks home. Total distance: 0.4 miles. Estimated time: twelve minutes if we walked briskly, fifteen if we took it easy.\n\nActual time: forty-seven minutes.\n\nI know because I have a stopwatch app on my phone, and I started it the moment we left the house.\n\nHere's what happened:\n\n0:00 - Left the house. Speedy stood on the porch and sniffed the air.\n0:23 - Still sniffing the air.\n0:41 - Speedy took one step forward.\n0:58 - Speedy stopped to sniff a crack in the sidewalk.\n2:14 - Still sniffing the crack.\n2:15 - I tried to gently pull the leash. Speedy did not move.\n2:47 - Speedy finished sniffing the crack. Took three steps. Found another crack.\n3:12 - Sniffing the new crack.\n\nYou get the idea.\n\nIn forty-seven minutes, we made it two blocks. Speedy stopped to smell fourteen different things: three cracks, two patches of grass, one fire hydrant (for four minutes and twelve seconds—I timed it), one spot where there used to be a puddle but wasn't anymore, one perfectly normal section of concrete that I couldn't identify as special in any way, one leaf that had blown away before she finished smelling it, and five things I couldn't even see.\n\nI started a note on my phone called \"Speedy's Smell Log.\" It seemed important to document.\n\nBy the time we got home, I was exhausted, and Speedy looked exactly the same as when we'd left: calm, unhurried, mildly pleased with herself.\n\n\"How was the walk?\" Mom asked.\n\n\"We went two blocks.\"\n\n\"That's nice.\"\n\n\"It took forty-seven minutes.\"\n\n\"She's getting used to the neighborhood.\"\n\n\"She smelled things that don't exist, Mom. She smelled where a leaf USED to be.\"\n\nMom just smiled. \"Give her time.\"\n\nI didn't want to give her time. I wanted a dog who could keep up with me. Instead, I had a dog who treated every walk like a museum tour, stopping at each exhibit to fully appreciate its aroma.\n\n---\n\nLater that afternoon, I was sitting on the front porch, watching Speedy lie in the grass and do absolutely nothing, when I saw a kid walking across the parking lot of the apartment complex next door.\n\nHe was carrying a small glass tank with both hands, very carefully, like it contained something precious. Or dangerous. Or both.\n\nI recognized him from school—Ben something. He was in my grade but not my class. He was the quiet kid who always seemed to be thinking about something nobody else was thinking about.\n\n\"Hey,\" I called out. \"What's in the tank?\"\n\nHe stopped walking. Looked at me. Looked at the tank. Looked back at me.\n\n\"My chameleon,\" he said. His voice was completely flat, like he was reporting the weather.\n\n\"Cool. What color is it?\"\n\n\"Brown.\"\n\n\"Like, right now? Or—\"\n\n\"Always. It's brown. It doesn't change colors.\" He said this the same way you'd say \"the sky is blue\" or \"water is wet.\" Just a fact. \"Did you know chameleons can move their eyes independently? They can look at two different things at once.\"\n\n\"That's cool.\"\n\n\"Camo looks at two walls at the same time. That's his main activity.\"\n\nI wasn't sure if this was a joke. Ben's face gave no indication.\n\n\"I got a dog today,\" I said, gesturing at Speedy, who was still lying in the grass. \"She's supposed to be a runner. Her name is Speedy.\"\n\nBen looked at Speedy. Speedy didn't move.\n\n\"She doesn't look speedy.\"\n\n\"She's not. At all. She has three legs and stops to smell everything. Our first walk took forty-seven minutes to go two blocks.\"\n\n\"Did you know dogs can smell 10,000 to 100,000 times better than humans?\" Ben said. \"Forty-seven minutes for two blocks is actually pretty efficient if you think about all the information she's processing.\"\n\nI hadn't thought about it that way. It didn't make me feel better.\n\n\"What's wrong with your chameleon?\" I asked. \"Why won't it change colors?\"\n\nBen shrugged. One shoulder, minimal effort. \"I don't know. I've tried everything. Different lighting, different temperatures, different backgrounds. I even played him videos of other chameleons changing colors. He watched for a while, then looked away. I think he was unimpressed.\"\n\n\"That's... weird.\"\n\n\"It's fine. He's committed to being brown. I respect his commitment.\"\n\nI stared at Ben. Ben stared back. His face was completely neutral.\n\n\"I'm Maya,\" I said.\n\n\"I know. You're in Mrs. Patterson's class. I'm Ben.\"\n\n\"Your chameleon—\"\n\n\"Camo.\"\n\n\"Right. Camo. Does he do anything? Besides being brown?\"\n\n\"He eats. He sleeps. He looks at walls. Sometimes he looks at me, but I think that's accidental.\" Ben paused. \"Did you know chameleons can see ultraviolet light? He probably sees things I don't. Maybe that's why he doesn't care about regular colors. He's already seen better ones.\"\n\nI couldn't tell if Ben was sad about his broken chameleon or if this was just how he talked about everything. Either way, there was something almost peaceful about his acceptance. His chameleon was brown. That was a fact. He'd moved on.\n\n\"Want to sit down?\" I asked. \"I'm watching my dog do nothing. You could watch with me.\"\n\nBen considered this. Then he walked over and sat on the porch steps, setting the tank carefully beside him. Inside, a brown chameleon sat on a branch, being brown.\n\nWe sat there for a while, watching our disappointing pets.\n\n\"I wanted a dog that could run,\" I said eventually.\n\n\"I wanted a chameleon that would be impressive,\" Ben said. \"Something I could show people. Something that would do tricks. Or at least change colors.\"\n\n\"What happened?\"\n\n\"This.\" He gestured at the tank. \"He was the only one left at the pet store. The sign said 'LAST ONE—NEEDS A GOOD HOME.' I thought he'd be grateful. You know, try harder for me because I rescued him.\"\n\n\"Did he?\"\n\n\"He looked at me once. Then he looked at the wall. He's been looking at walls ever since.\"\n\nSpeedy lifted her head, sniffed the air, and put her head back down.\n\n\"Same,\" I said.\n\n---\n\nWhen Mom called me in for dinner, Leo came running up from wherever he'd been exploring, clutching his latest map.\n\n\"Maya! Maya! Look what I found!\"\n\n\"Not now, Leo.\"\n\n\"But I mapped the whole neighborhood! I found seventeen hiding spots! Some are really small. I ranked them by size!\"\n\n\"That's great.\"\n\n\"And there's one really good one that I couldn't fit into. It's under something. I marked it with a star because it's important.\"\n\nI wasn't really listening. I was too busy thinking about Speedy, and Ben's chameleon, and how the day was supposed to go differently.\n\n\"Maybe you can help me check it tomorrow?\" Leo asked. \"The small one. I need someone with longer arms.\"\n\n\"Maybe,\" I said, which is what you say when you mean \"no but I don't want to argue.\"\n\nLeo ran inside, still talking about his map, about hiding spots and stars and things that were \"too small for now but maybe later.\"\n\nI looked back at Speedy. She was standing now—slowly, like even standing was an activity that deserved careful consideration. She walked over to me, three legs moving in an awkward rhythm that somehow looked graceful, and put her head against my knee.\n\n\"You're not what I wanted,\" I told her.\n\nShe wagged her tail. Slowly.\n\n\"But I guess you're what I got.\"\n\nShe leaned into my leg, warm and solid and completely unhurried.\n\nI scratched behind her ears, and for a second, I stopped thinking about spreadsheets and plans and everything that had gone wrong. For a second, I just had a dog, and the dog was here, and that was something.\n\nIt wasn't enough. But it was something.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"The Club Nobody Wanted","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# The Club Nobody Wanted\n\nBy the end of the first week, I had started keeping official records.\n\nThe spreadsheet was called \"Speedy's Smell Log\" and it lived in my phone's notes app. Every walk, I tracked: time of day, weather, total duration, number of smell stops, average duration of each stop, and \"notable objects sniffed.\"\n\nAfter seven walks, the data was clear:\n\n- Average smell stops per walk: 14.3\n- Average duration per stop: 47 seconds\n- Longest single stop: 4 minutes 12 seconds (fire hydrant, corner of Oak and Maple)\n- Most confusing stop: 2 minutes 38 seconds (nothing visible—possibly a memory of a smell? Do smells leave ghosts?)\n- Total distance covered in one week: 2.1 miles\n- Total time spent: 5 hours 23 minutes\n\nIf you do the math, that's about 0.4 miles per hour. I could crawl faster than that. I could probably roll faster than that.\n\n\"You're collecting data,\" Ben said when I showed him. He was sitting on my porch again, Camo's tank beside him. This had become a routine. Every afternoon, Ben came over, and we watched our disappointing pets together.\n\n\"Data helps you understand things,\" I said.\n\n\"Does it help?\"\n\n\"No. But at least I know exactly how much time I'm wasting.\"\n\nBen nodded slowly. \"Did you know some scientists spent twenty years studying why chameleons change colors? Twenty years. And the answer was basically 'mood and temperature.' I read their whole paper. Camo still won't change colors.\"\n\n\"Maybe he's always in the same mood.\"\n\n\"Brown mood.\" Ben looked at his chameleon. Camo was sitting on his branch, looking at the side of the tank. \"I respect it, honestly. Most people change who they are depending on who's watching. Camo is the same no matter what. That's integrity.\"\n\nI couldn't tell if Ben actually believed this or if he'd just convinced himself to feel better about his useless pet. Either way, it was an impressive spin.\n\nThat's when Jenna showed up.\n\n---\n\nJenna Price lived three streets over, and I knew her from school—everyone knew Jenna from school. She was loud, confident, always in the middle of everything. She had the kind of personality that filled a room, the kind of laugh you could hear from the cafeteria in the parking lot.\n\nSo I was surprised when she walked up to my porch looking like someone had just told her Christmas was cancelled.\n\nShe was carrying a cat carrier. It looked empty.\n\n\"Is that for your cat?\" I asked.\n\nJenna set the carrier down on the porch with a thunk. \"She's IN there.\"\n\nI leaned over and looked through the mesh door. I saw: nothing. A blanket, a small toy, empty space.\n\n\"There's no cat in here.\"\n\n\"She's in the CORNER.\"\n\nI looked again. There were no corners. Cat carriers are rounded. \"Jenna, there is literally no cat—\"\n\n\"She's THERE. She just... blends.\"\n\nBen peered into the carrier. \"Is she a chameleon?\"\n\n\"She's a CAT, Ben. A gray fluffy cat named Duchess.\"\n\n\"A gray fluffy cat should be visible.\"\n\n\"You would THINK.\" Jenna collapsed onto the porch steps, dropping her head into her hands. \"I've had her for three weeks. I've seen her twice. TWICE. Both times she was mid-disappearance—like I caught the last half-second of her leaving a room.\"\n\nI looked at the carrier again. Still empty. \"How do you know she's real?\"\n\nJenna's head snapped up. \"Excuse me?\"\n\n\"I'm just asking. Have you considered that maybe you don't actually have a cat?\"\n\n\"The LITTER BOX is used, Maya. I don't know what else would be using the litter box. And the food disappears. Every day, the food bowl is empty in the morning.\"\n\n\"Could be raccoons,\" Ben said helpfully.\n\n\"Raccoons that use a litter box?\"\n\n\"Did you know raccoons can be litter trained? They're actually very—\"\n\n\"BEN.\"\n\nBen went quiet.\n\nJenna took a deep breath. \"I wanted a cat I could photograph. I started an Instagram for her—@duchess_the_magnificent—before I even brought her home. I had plans. Photo shoots. Cute outfits. She was going to be FAMOUS.\"\n\nI pulled out my phone and found the account. Jenna had 52 posts. I scrolled through them.\n\nPhoto of an empty windowsill. Caption: *Sunbathing.*\nPhoto of an empty cat bed. Caption: *Napping beauty.*\nPhoto of a slightly rumpled blanket. Caption: *She was just here. I SAW her.*\nPhoto of a single clump of gray fur on a pillow. Caption: *PROOF. Tell me she's not real NOW.*\n\nThe comments were brutal:\n*where's the cat*\n*is this a joke account*\n*I literally see nothing*\n*are you okay???*\n\nAnd Jenna's replies:\n*She's there. Look harder.*\n*Behind the lamp. You can almost see her tail.*\n*That's her EAR in the corner. Obviously.*\n\n\"This is deeply unhinged,\" I said.\n\n\"I KNOW.\" Jenna grabbed the carrier and shook it gently. Nothing moved inside. \"Duchess. DUCHESS. Please just show them you exist.\"\n\nSilence.\n\nThen, from somewhere inside the carrier—maybe—a very soft meow.\n\n\"SEE?\" Jenna said triumphantly.\n\n\"I didn't see anything. I HEARD something. That could have been you.\"\n\n\"Why would I meow at my own cat carrier?\"\n\n\"Why would you post fifty pictures of an empty room?\"\n\nJenna glared at me. I glared back. Ben watched us both with mild interest, like we were a nature documentary.\n\n\"Let's start over,\" I said. \"I'm Maya. I have a three-legged dog who walks slower than continental drift. Ben has a chameleon who only does one color. And you have... a cat who may or may not exist.\"\n\n\"She EXISTS.\"\n\n\"We believe you,\" Ben said. He didn't sound like he believed her.\n\n\"This is Ben,\" I continued. \"He says facts about animals when he's uncomfortable.\"\n\n\"Did you know cats can make over 100 different vocal sounds? Dogs can only make about 10.\" Ben paused. \"That wasn't because I'm uncomfortable. That was just relevant.\"\n\nJenna looked at him for a long moment. Then she looked at me. Then she looked at Speedy, who was lying in the grass, sniffing a dandelion with the concentration of a detective analyzing evidence.\n\n\"What's wrong with your dog?\"\n\n\"She stops to smell everything. Our walks take forever.\"\n\n\"What's wrong with his lizard?\"\n\n\"Chameleon,\" Ben corrected.\n\n\"Whatever.\"\n\n\"He won't change colors. He's committed to brown.\"\n\nJenna sat back down on the porch. She looked exhausted in a way that had nothing to do with being tired.\n\n\"So we all have broken pets,\" she said.\n\n\"They're not broken,\" I said, though I wasn't sure I believed it. \"They're just... not what we expected.\"\n\n\"Same thing.\"\n\nNobody argued with that.\n\n---\n\nThat's how the Wrong Pet Club started.\n\nIt wasn't an official thing at first. It was just the three of us, sitting on my porch every afternoon, comparing disappointments.\n\nBen would update us on Camo's latest non-color-change. (\"Today I tried putting him on a blue background. He stayed brown. I put him on a red background. Still brown. I think he's making a statement.\")\n\nJenna would report on Duchess sightings—or the lack of them. She'd started keeping a log, like a field researcher tracking an endangered species:\n\n> *Day 16, 0800 hours: Subject not visible. Food bowl empty. Litter evidence suggests activity between 0200-0400. No visual confirmation.*\n\n> *Day 18, 1423 hours: Movement detected in peripheral vision. Gray blur, heading north. Duration: sub-one-second. Added to \"inconclusive\" tally.*\n\n> *Day 21, 0312 hours: Auditory event. Single meow, origin unknown. Checked all rooms. Nothing.*\n\nAnd I would share my Smell Log data, complete with charts and averages.\n\n\"This is sad,\" Jenna said one afternoon, looking at all of our notes. \"We're documenting our failures.\"\n\n\"Data helps you understand things,\" I said.\n\n\"Does understanding help?\"\n\n\"Not really.\"\n\nBut there was something comforting about it anyway. At least we weren't alone in our disappointment. At least someone else understood what it felt like to get the wrong pet.\n\nThat's when Leo showed up.\n\n---\n\n\"MAYA!\"\n\nMy brother came running around the corner of the house, waving a piece of paper over his head like he'd just discovered treasure. Which, knowing Leo, was probably exactly what he thought.\n\n\"I finished my new map!\"\n\n\"That's great, Leo.\"\n\n\"It's HIDING SPOTS. Secret ones. I ranked them!\"\n\nHe shoved the paper at me. I looked at it because it was easier than arguing.\n\nIt was actually impressive, in a weird way. Leo had drawn our whole neighborhood—streets, houses, trees, fences—and marked about twenty different spots with X's. Each X had a number next to it, and there was a legend at the bottom:\n\n*HIDING SPOT RANKINGS*\n*1 = Easy to find*\n*2 = Medium hard*\n*3 = Really hidden*\n*4 = So secret even I forgot where it was*\n*STAR = Need help to check*\n\nMost of the spots were numbered 1 or 2. A few were 3. One, near the edge of the map, had a star next to it.\n\n\"What's the star one?\" I asked.\n\n\"It's REALLY small. Under something. I can see it but I can't fit.\" Leo bounced on his heels. \"Will you help me check it? Please? It's important.\"\n\n\"Why is it important?\"\n\n\"Because I need to know what's there!\"\n\n\"Why?\"\n\n\"Because WHAT IF something is there?\"\n\nThis was Leo logic. He didn't want to find anything specific. He just wanted to find SOMETHING. Any something. He'd been like this since he was four, always looking under rocks and behind bushes, always convinced there was treasure hidden everywhere if you just knew where to look.\n\n\"Maybe later,\" I said.\n\n\"You always say that.\"\n\n\"And I always mean it.\"\n\nLeo pouted, but he was distracted a moment later by a beetle on the porch railing. He crouched down to examine it, probably planning to add it to some map of \"Beetles I Have Seen.\"\n\n\"He makes maps?\" Jenna asked.\n\n\"Of everything. He has one called 'Snails I Have Met.' Every snail in the neighborhood, named and categorized.\"\n\n\"That's... thorough.\"\n\n\"He's six.\"\n\nBen was looking at Leo's hiding spot map with genuine interest. \"This is actually well-designed. Clear legend, consistent symbols, accurate scale.\"\n\n\"Please don't encourage him.\"\n\n\"I'm just saying. If he ever gets lost, this map would help you find him.\"\n\nI took the map from Ben and handed it back to Leo. \"Here. Go find more hiding spots.\"\n\nLeo grabbed it and ran off, already scanning the yard for potential discoveries.\n\n\"Cute kid,\" Jenna said.\n\n\"He's exhausting.\"\n\n\"Same thing.\"\n\n---\n\nAn hour later, we were still on the porch when an old woman walked by—Mrs. Park from two houses down. She was nice, quiet, always wearing cardigans even in summer.\n\n\"Hello, children,\" she said. \"Have any of you seen a gold watch? I've been looking for it for months now. It was my husband's.\"\n\nWe all shook our heads.\n\n\"I lost it somewhere in the neighborhood. I was gardening, and then I went for a walk, and somewhere along the way...\" She trailed off, looking sad. \"It's probably in a storm drain by now. But I keep hoping.\"\n\n\"Did you know metal detectors can find things up to 12 inches underground?\" Ben said. \"Depending on the soil composition.\"\n\nMrs. Park smiled, but it was the kind of smile adults give when they don't know how to respond to a fact. \"That's nice, dear. If you see anything shiny, let me know.\"\n\nShe walked on.\n\n\"That's sad,\" Jenna said. \"Losing something from someone who died.\"\n\n\"Her husband died?\" I asked.\n\n\"Like two years ago. My mom told me. Mrs. Park still talks about him sometimes.\"\n\nWe sat with that for a moment. Then Jenna shook her head and stood up.\n\n\"I should go. I need to check on Duchess. Make sure she still technically exists.\"\n\n\"Good luck,\" I said.\n\n\"Luck doesn't help. EVIDENCE helps. I'm setting up a motion-activated camera tonight. If she moves, I'll catch her.\"\n\n\"Did you know cats can move fast enough to—\" Ben started.\n\n\"GOODNIGHT, BEN.\"\n\nJenna picked up her carrier—still apparently containing an invisible cat—and walked home.\n\nBen stood up too, carefully lifting Camo's tank. \"Same time tomorrow?\"\n\n\"Same time.\"\n\nHe nodded and left.\n\nI sat on the porch alone, watching Speedy sniff the spot where the beetle used to be. She sniffed it for nearly a minute, even though the beetle was long gone.\n\n\"You're weird,\" I told her.\n\nShe wagged her tail.\n\nSomewhere in the house, I could hear Leo talking to himself, probably planning his next map. Something about \"places that smell funny\" and \"maybe treasure.\"\n\nI picked up my phone and added an entry to the Smell Log:\n\n*6:47 PM - Beetle location (vacant). Duration: 58 seconds. Notes: Beetle departed 23 minutes prior. Speedy does not seem to understand time.*\n\nThen I put my phone away and just sat there, watching my weird slow dog smell things that weren't there anymore.\n\nThe Wrong Pet Club. It wasn't a real club yet. We didn't have rules or meetings or a secret handshake.\n\nBut we had each other.\n\nAnd we had our wrong pets.\n\nAnd for now, that was enough.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Parade Problem","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# The Parade Problem\n\nThe Greenbrook Annual Pet Parade was announced on a Tuesday.\n\nI saw the flyers on my way to school—bright yellow paper stapled to every telephone pole and taped to every shop window. There was a cartoon dog on the front, wearing a tiny top hat, looking extremely pleased with itself.\n\n**GREENBROOK PET PARADE!**\n**Saturday, October 15th**\n**Categories: Best Trick, Best Costume, Most Photogenic, Best in Show!**\n**Prizes! Ribbons! Fun for the whole family!**\n\nI took a picture of the flyer and sent it to the Wrong Pet Club group chat.\n\n**Maya:** did you see this\n**Jenna:** NO\n**Jenna:** absolutely not\n**Jenna:** i cannot enter a pet that no one can see\n**Ben:** Camo's best trick is sitting on a branch. He does it automatically.\n\nI stared at my phone and tried to imagine entering Speedy in \"Best Trick.\"\n\n\"And what trick will your dog be performing today?\"\n\n\"She stops walking. For forty-seven seconds. Every time she smells something.\"\n\n\"That's... not really a trick.\"\n\n\"She does it without being asked.\"\n\nI put my phone away.\n\n---\n\nAt lunch, the three of us sat together in the corner of the cafeteria, which had become our usual spot. Ben had his chameleon facts book open. Jenna had her phone out, scrolling through @duchess_the_magnificent comments.\n\n\"Someone asked if my account is a social experiment,\" she said. \"They think I'm making an artistic statement about the nature of absence.\"\n\n\"Are you?\"\n\n\"I'm making a statement about how my cat WON'T SHOW HER FACE.\"\n\nShe put her phone down and looked at us seriously. \"I can't do the parade. I have 52 posts and zero cat photos. If I show up with an empty carrier, people will think I'm insane.\"\n\n\"You kind of are,\" I said.\n\n\"I'm DEDICATED. There's a difference.\"\n\nBen turned a page in his book. \"Did you know chameleons don't really change color for camouflage? It's mostly for communication and temperature regulation. The whole 'blending in' thing is a myth.\"\n\n\"Fascinating,\" Jenna said flatly. \"Does Camo communicate?\"\n\n\"He communicates that he's brown.\"\n\n\"That's not communication. That's just... existing.\"\n\n\"Existing is a statement.\"\n\nI couldn't tell if Ben actually believed this stuff or if he'd just gotten really good at philosophical deflection. Either way, he never seemed upset about Camo. He'd achieved some kind of zen acceptance that I couldn't manage with Speedy.\n\n\"What about you?\" Jenna asked me. \"Are you entering?\"\n\nI thought about it. I thought about Speedy's smell stops, her three-legged shuffle, her complete disinterest in doing anything quickly or impressively.\n\n\"What would I even enter for? Best Trick? Her trick is standing still.\"\n\n\"You could do Most Photogenic,\" Jenna suggested.\n\n\"She photographs fine. She just doesn't DO anything in photos. She looks like she's waiting for the photo to be over so she can go back to smelling things.\"\n\n\"Best Costume?\"\n\n\"She'd stop to smell the costume before we got to the stage.\"\n\nWe sat in defeated silence.\n\nThen Ben said, \"What if we entered together? As a team?\"\n\nJenna and I looked at him.\n\n\"A team of what?\" I asked.\n\n\"The Wrong Pet Club. That could be our category. We're not competing to be the BEST. We're competing to be... us.\"\n\n\"That's not a category,\" Jenna said.\n\n\"We could make it one.\"\n\n\"You can't just make up categories.\"\n\n\"Why not? We made up a club.\"\n\nHe had a point. The Wrong Pet Club wasn't official. We didn't have rules or membership cards or anything. We were just three kids with disappointing pets who complained together.\n\n\"So what would we do?\" I asked. \"Walk on stage with a slow dog, a brown chameleon, and an empty cat carrier?\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"That's... actually kind of funny.\"\n\nJenna was quiet for a moment. Then she smiled—a real smile, not the forced one she'd been wearing since Duchess started her invisibility campaign.\n\n\"The Wrong Pet Club,\" she said. \"Entering the pet parade with the wrong pets.\"\n\n\"It's stupid,\" I said.\n\n\"It's VERY stupid.\"\n\n\"Let's do it.\"\n\n---\n\nAfter school, we had our first official Wrong Pet Club meeting at my house.\n\nThe agenda:\n1. Discuss parade strategy\n2. Practice introductions\n3. Complain about our pets (ongoing)\n\nSpeedy was lying on the porch, sleeping. Camo was in his tank, looking at a leaf. Duchess was in her carrier, allegedly.\n\n\"Okay,\" Jenna said, pulling out her phone. \"I've been thinking about this. If we're going to enter as a joke, we should COMMIT to the joke. Like, really lean into it.\"\n\n\"What does that mean?\"\n\n\"I made a presentation.\"\n\nShe turned her phone around. The first slide said: **THE WRONG PET CLUB: PARADE STRATEGY**\n\n\"You made a presentation in the last two hours?\"\n\n\"I'm motivated when I'm angry.\"\n\nShe swiped to the next slide: **OUR PETS' ABILITIES**\n\nUnder Speedy, she'd written: *Smelling things. Standing still. Walking slowly. Being patient.*\n\nUnder Camo: *Being brown. Looking at walls. Existing.*\n\nUnder Duchess: *Disappearing. Possibly not existing. Evidence suggests real.*\n\n\"This is accurate but painful,\" I said.\n\n\"That's the point. We're not pretending they're good. We're saying: 'These are our pets. They're weird. We love them anyway.'\"\n\n\"Do we love them?\" I asked.\n\nJenna paused. \"I love the IDEA of Duchess. The actual Duchess remains unconfirmed.\"\n\nBen had been quiet this whole time. Now he spoke up. \"I don't know if I love Camo. But I respect him. He knows who he is. He doesn't change for anyone.\"\n\n\"Because he CAN'T change.\"\n\n\"Maybe. Or maybe he won't. There's a difference.\"\n\nI looked at Speedy, still sleeping on the porch. Did I love her? She wasn't what I wanted. She wasn't fast or athletic or anything on my spreadsheet. She was slow and stubborn and she smelled things that didn't exist.\n\nBut she was mine. And there was something kind of nice about that.\n\n\"Fine,\" I said. \"We'll enter. But I'm not wearing a costume.\"\n\n\"Nobody's wearing costumes,\" Jenna said. \"The pets are the statement.\"\n\n\"What statement?\"\n\n\"That wrong is just... different. And different isn't bad.\"\n\nIt was almost inspiring. Almost.\n\n---\n\nThat night, Leo knocked on my bedroom door.\n\n\"Maya? Are you busy?\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\nHe came in anyway. He was holding his map—the one with the hiding spots—but it looked different now. More notes. More symbols. One spot was circled three times in red marker.\n\n\"I need your help tomorrow,\" he said. \"With the star spot.\"\n\n\"I told you, maybe later.\"\n\n\"You've said that for a WEEK.\"\n\n\"And I'll keep saying it until later happens.\"\n\nLeo's face did something complicated. He wasn't crying, but he wasn't far from it. \"But it's IMPORTANT, Maya. I've been looking for something for Mrs. Park. Her watch. The gold one. I think I know where it might be, but I can't fit to check.\"\n\nI sat up. \"You're looking for Mrs. Park's watch?\"\n\n\"She lost it. She told us. Remember? And I've been mapping all the places things could get lost—cracks and holes and drains and hiding spots. And there's one spot that's REALLY small, under a thing, near where she said she was gardening. And I think maybe—\"\n\n\"Leo.\" I held up my hand. \"That watch is gone. It's been months. It probably washed down a drain or got picked up by a bird or something. You're not going to find it.\"\n\n\"But what if I DO?\"\n\n\"You won't.\"\n\n\"But what IF?\"\n\nI sighed. Leo's optimism was exhausting. He genuinely believed he could find a watch that had been missing for months, just by crawling around and checking hiding spots.\n\n\"Maybe this weekend,\" I said. \"After the parade.\"\n\n\"PROMISE?\"\n\n\"I... fine. I promise. After the parade, I'll help you check your dumb hiding spot.\"\n\nLeo's face lit up. \"It's not dumb. It's SECRET. And small. And kind of under a shed, I think. At the old Miller property. Where nobody goes.\"\n\n\"Great. Sounds safe.\"\n\n\"It IS safe. I checked. Well, I checked from the outside. I couldn't fit inside. That's why I need HELP.\"\n\nHe left, clutching his map, already planning his treasure hunt.\n\nI went back to my homework, but I couldn't focus. I kept thinking about Mrs. Park's face when she'd asked about the watch. How sad she'd looked. How hopeful, even though she knew it was probably gone.\n\nAnd Leo, making maps, looking in every crack and hole, trying to find something that would make a sad old lady happy.\n\nIt was sweet. And probably pointless.\n\nBut still sweet.\n\n---\n\nThe next few days passed in a blur of parade preparation, which mostly meant NOT preparing.\n\nWe practiced walking on stage—Speedy stopped to smell the porch three times.\n\nWe practiced holding our pets up for the judges—Camo fell asleep, Duchess was not visible.\n\nWe practiced explaining what made our pets special—we couldn't think of anything that sounded good.\n\n\"This is a disaster,\" Jenna said on Thursday afternoon.\n\n\"We knew it would be a disaster,\" I reminded her.\n\n\"I thought it would be a FUNNY disaster. This is just regular disaster.\"\n\nBen was examining Camo through the glass of his tank. \"He changed color a little today. I think.\"\n\nWe all leaned in to look. Camo was sitting on his branch. Brown. Same brown as always.\n\n\"He looks exactly the same,\" Jenna said.\n\n\"The brown is slightly different. Warmer. See?\"\n\nI squinted. \"I don't see anything.\"\n\n\"It's subtle. You have to really know brown to see it.\"\n\n\"Ben, that's the saddest thing you've ever said.\"\n\n\"Thank you.\"\n\nI wasn't sure if he was being sarcastic. With Ben, you could never tell.\n\n---\n\nFriday night, the night before the parade, I couldn't sleep.\n\nI lay in bed and listened to the house settle around me. Dad snoring down the hall. The refrigerator humming in the kitchen. And somewhere outside, a dog barking—not Speedy, she never barked, she just sniffed—some other dog, living some other life.\n\nI thought about the parade. About walking on stage with my slow, three-legged dog who wouldn't do any tricks. About standing next to Ben and his brown chameleon, Jenna and her invisible cat.\n\nWe were going to look ridiculous.\n\nAnd somehow, that felt okay.\n\nI heard footsteps in the hall—Leo, probably getting water. He did that sometimes, wandering around at night, checking on things. Making sure everything was where it should be.\n\nI thought about his map. The star spot. The hiding place he couldn't fit into.\n\n*After the parade*, I'd said. *I promise.*\n\nI'd probably forget. I always forgot Leo's promises. He'd remind me, and I'd say \"maybe tomorrow,\" and eventually he'd stop asking.\n\nThat's how it always went.\n\nI turned over and closed my eyes and tried not to think about watches or hiding spots or anything except the parade.\n\nTomorrow was going to be weird.\n\nBut at least we'd be weird together.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Lost","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Lost\n\nThe morning of the parade, Leo was gone.\n\nNot missing-missing. Not at first. Just... not in his room when Mom went to wake him up. His bed was made (badly, but made), his pajamas were on the floor, and his backpack was gone. So were his rain boots, even though it wasn't raining.\n\n\"He probably went to play in the backyard,\" Dad said.\n\nHe wasn't in the backyard.\n\n\"Maybe he walked to the park.\"\n\nHe wasn't at the park.\n\n\"He's six,\" Mom said, and her voice had that edge to it now, the one that meant she was trying not to panic. \"Where would a six-year-old GO?\"\n\nThat's when I saw his map.\n\nIt was on his desk, pinned under a rock he'd collected last month (labeled, of course: \"ROCK FROM MR. DAVIDSON'S DRIVEWAY - SPARKLY\"). The hiding spots map. The one he'd been working on for weeks.\n\nOne spot was circled three times in red. Next to it, in Leo's crooked handwriting:\n\n**THE SMALL ONE**\n**UNDER THE SHED**\n**TODAY!!!**\n**NEED FLASHLIGHT**\n\nMy stomach dropped.\n\n\"Mom,\" I said. \"I think I know where he went.\"\n\n---\n\nThe old Miller property was four blocks away, at the edge of the neighborhood where the houses stopped and the overgrown lots began. The Millers had moved out years ago, and nobody had bought the place since. There was a rusted fence, a yard full of weeds, and a shed that looked like it might collapse if you breathed on it.\n\nAnd apparently, under that shed, there was a hiding spot that Leo had been dying to explore.\n\nA hiding spot he thought might contain Mrs. Park's lost watch.\n\nI ran the whole way. Speedy, somehow, kept up—three legs pumping, ears flying, not stopping to smell a single thing. It was the fastest I'd ever seen her move.\n\nMom and Dad were calling people, organizing a search. I should have waited for them. I should have been responsible and patient and done everything properly.\n\nBut Leo had been trying to show me that map for a week. He'd asked for my help, and I'd said \"maybe later.\" Over and over. \"Maybe later.\"\n\nAnd now he was gone, and maybe later was too late.\n\n---\n\nI texted the group chat while I ran:\n\n**Maya:** leo is missing\n**Maya:** i think he went to the old miller property\n**Maya:** the shed there\n**Maya:** i'm going now\n\nBy the time I reached the property, Ben and Jenna were already there.\n\nBen had Camo's tank strapped to his chest with a makeshift harness. Jenna was carrying Duchess's carrier.\n\n\"Why did you bring your pets?\" I gasped, out of breath.\n\n\"I don't know,\" Ben said. \"It felt important.\"\n\n\"The carrier was by the door,\" Jenna said. \"I grabbed it without thinking.\"\n\nWe stood at the rusted fence, looking at the overgrown yard. The shed was at the back, tilted slightly, half-covered in vines. It looked like something from a horror movie.\n\n\"Leo?\" I shouted. \"LEO!\"\n\nNothing.\n\n\"Maybe he's not here,\" Jenna said.\n\n\"He's here. I know it. He's been planning this for WEEKS.\" I pulled up his map on my phone—I'd taken a picture of it last week, when he wouldn't stop showing it to me. \"Look. The star spot. It's right there, under the shed.\"\n\n\"Under it?\"\n\n\"There's a crawlspace or something. He said he couldn't fit, but he wanted to check it. He thought that's where Mrs. Park's watch might be.\"\n\n\"Mrs. Park's watch?\" Ben asked.\n\n\"It's a long story. He's been looking for it. Like a treasure hunt.\"\n\nWe climbed the fence—it was wobbly but held—and pushed through the weeds toward the shed. The closer we got, the worse it looked. The wood was rotten in places. There were holes in the walls. The door was hanging off one hinge.\n\n\"LEO!\" I shouted again.\n\nThis time, I heard something. Faint. Muffled. Coming from underneath.\n\n\"MAYA?\"\n\n\"LEO! Where are you?\"\n\n\"I'M STUCK!\"\n\nI dropped to my knees and looked under the shed. There was a gap between the bottom of the structure and the ground—maybe a foot high, crawling with shadows. I couldn't see anything.\n\n\"Are you hurt?\"\n\n\"No! But I can't get out! There's a hole and I fell in and now I can't climb back up!\"\n\n\"Okay. Okay. We're going to get you out.\" I looked at Ben and Jenna. \"We need to get under there.\"\n\n\"I'll go,\" Ben said immediately.\n\n\"You?\"\n\n\"I'm the smallest. And—\" He hesitated. \"And I need to do this.\"\n\nBefore I could argue, he was already on his belly, crawling into the gap under the shed. Camo's tank was still strapped to his chest, the chameleon inside looking as unbothered as ever.\n\n\"I can't see anything,\" Ben called back. \"It's too dark.\"\n\n\"Leo! Keep talking so Ben can find you!\"\n\n\"I FOUND THE WATCH!\" Leo's voice echoed from somewhere in the darkness. \"MRS. PARK'S WATCH! IT WAS HERE THE WHOLE TIME! BUT NOW I'M IN A HOLE AND I CAN'T—\"\n\n\"I hear him,\" Ben said. \"I'm going toward the voice.\"\n\nWe waited. It felt like hours but was probably only minutes.\n\nThen Ben's voice, tight with worry: \"There's a hole. Like a foundation crack or something. He fell in. It's about four feet deep. I can see him but I can't reach him.\"\n\n\"Can he climb out?\"\n\n\"The walls are dirt. They keep crumbling when he tries.\"\n\nI looked around frantically. We needed rope, or a ladder, or SOMETHING—\n\nThat's when Speedy started pulling at her leash.\n\nI'd almost forgotten she was there. She'd followed me the whole way, keeping pace, not stopping to smell anything. But now she was straining forward, nose to the ground, sniffing with an intensity I'd never seen.\n\n\"What are you—\" I started.\n\nShe pulled harder. Not toward the shed, but to the side of it. Around to the back.\n\n\"Speedy, this isn't the time for—\"\n\nBut she wasn't doing her usual slow, methodical sniffing. This was different. Purposeful. Fast.\n\nI let her lead me.\n\nShe went around the back of the shed, nose working constantly. Then she stopped at a pile of old boards and debris, half-covered in vines. She pawed at it. Whined.\n\n\"There's nothing here,\" I said.\n\nShe pawed again. More insistent.\n\nI started pulling at the boards. Jenna appeared beside me and helped. We threw aside rotten wood and rusty metal and years of leaves until—\n\nA hole. Another way into the crawlspace. Bigger than the gap at the front.\n\n\"BEN!\" I shouted. \"There's another entrance! At the back!\"\n\nA moment later, Ben's face appeared in the hole, dirt-streaked and relieved. \"I see it! I can get to Leo from here!\"\n\nHe crawled toward us, then dropped down into the hole where Leo was stuck. I heard scuffling, then Leo's voice, high with relief: \"BEN! You found me!\"\n\n\"Your sister's dog found you. I just followed.\"\n\nThey helped each other climb out of the hole—Leo first, then Ben. Leo was dirty and tear-streaked, but he was grinning. In his hand, clutched tight, was a gold watch.\n\n\"I FOUND IT!\" he said. \"I knew it was here! I KNEW it!\"\n\nI hugged him so hard I probably bruised something.\n\n---\n\nWe were walking back toward the street—all of us exhausted, filthy, and shaky with relief—when Jenna suddenly stopped.\n\n\"Wait.\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\nShe was looking at her cat carrier. Very carefully, she lifted it up and looked through the mesh.\n\nDuchess was inside.\n\nNot hiding. Not crouched in a corner that didn't exist. Just sitting there, calm and gray and fluffy, looking back at Jenna like this was a perfectly normal thing.\n\n\"When did you—\" Jenna started. \"How did—\"\n\n\"She was in there the whole time,\" Ben said. \"I saw her when we were climbing the fence. I thought you knew.\"\n\n\"I DIDN'T know. She's never IN there. I just carry it out of HABIT.\" Jenna was staring at her cat like she'd just witnessed a miracle. \"Duchess. You're here. You're actually HERE.\"\n\nDuchess meowed. A single, soft sound.\n\n\"That's the first time she's meowed at me when I could SEE her,\" Jenna whispered.\n\nWe all stood there for a moment, looking at the cat who finally decided to exist.\n\nThen Leo tugged at my sleeve. \"Maya. The watch. We have to give it to Mrs. Park.\"\n\nI looked at the watch in his hand. It was old and gold and scratched from its time underground, but it was there. Real. Found.\n\n\"Yeah,\" I said. \"We do.\"\n\n---\n\nMrs. Park was in her front yard when we walked up, still dirty and disheveled from the rescue mission. She was talking to my mom, who looked like she'd aged ten years in the last hour.\n\n\"THERE you are!\" Mom grabbed Leo and hugged him, then started the cycle of relief-turning-to-anger that I knew would last for the rest of the day. \"What were you THINKING? You could have been HURT! You could have—\"\n\n\"Mom,\" Leo said, squirming. \"Mom. MOM. I found it.\"\n\nHe held up the watch.\n\nMrs. Park went very still.\n\n\"That's—\" she started. \"That's—\"\n\n\"Your husband's watch,\" Leo said. \"You said you lost it near your garden. But I checked all around your garden and it wasn't there. So I made maps of everywhere things could go, and I found a path that leads from your house to the old Miller property, and I thought maybe it fell out of your pocket while you were walking and rolled somewhere, and I checked all the hiding spots on the path, and the last one was under the shed, and—\"\n\n\"Leo,\" I said gently. \"Breathe.\"\n\n\"—and it was THERE. Right where I thought. In a hole under the shed. I found it.\"\n\nMrs. Park was crying. Not sad crying—the other kind. She took the watch from Leo's hand and held it like it was made of something precious. Which, to her, it was.\n\n\"My William gave me this watch on our wedding day,\" she said. \"I've been looking for it for so long. I thought it was gone forever.\"\n\n\"It was just hiding,\" Leo said. \"Everything hides somewhere. You just have to find where.\"\n\nMrs. Park hugged him. Then she hugged me. Then she hugged Ben and Jenna, who looked startled but didn't resist.\n\n\"Thank you,\" she said. \"All of you. Thank you.\"\n\n---\n\nLater, after the lectures and the relief and the long hot showers, I sat on the porch with Speedy.\n\nThe parade was in two hours. We were still entered. We were still going to walk on stage with our wrong pets and probably embarrass ourselves.\n\nBut something felt different now.\n\nSpeedy had found the way in. Her nose—the same nose that spent forty-seven seconds smelling a fire hydrant, the same nose that stopped to sniff things that weren't there anymore—had found Leo.\n\nShe wasn't slow because she was broken. She was slow because she was THOROUGH.\n\n\"You found him,\" I said.\n\nShe wagged her tail. Slowly, like always.\n\n\"I thought you were smelling nothing. All those times. All those stops. But you were paying attention, weren't you? You were noticing things.\"\n\nShe put her head on my knee.\n\n\"I wanted a fast dog,\" I said. \"I wanted a dog who could keep up with me. But maybe I'm the one who needs to keep up with you.\"\n\nSpeedy closed her eyes, content.\n\nI scratched behind her ears and watched the street and thought about all the things I'd missed because I was too busy rushing.\n\nMaybe wrong wasn't wrong.\n\nMaybe wrong was just different.\n\nAnd maybe different was exactly what I needed.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"The Right Pets","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# The Right Pets\n\nThe Greenbrook Annual Pet Parade was held in the town square at 3 PM.\n\nBy the time we got there, I'd almost forgotten we were supposed to perform. The whole morning had been so strange—Leo disappearing, finding him under the shed, Mrs. Park crying over her watch—that the parade felt like something from another life.\n\nBut here we were. The Wrong Pet Club. Ready to be weird in public.\n\nThe square was packed with kids and their pets. I saw golden retrievers with ribbons in their fur, cats in tiny costumes, a rabbit wearing a cape, and one extremely confused guinea pig in a princess dress. Everyone looked prepared. Everyone looked confident.\n\nWe looked like we'd just crawled out of a ditch.\n\nWhich, technically, we had.\n\n\"Maybe we shouldn't do this,\" I said.\n\n\"We already signed up,\" Jenna replied. \"They called our names on the list.\"\n\n\"We could just... not go up.\"\n\n\"And waste my presentation?\" She pulled out her phone. \"I updated it. New title: THE WRONG PET CLUB: WHY OUR PETS ARE ACTUALLY GREAT.\"\n\n\"You updated it in the last two hours?\"\n\n\"I'm motivated when I have feelings.\"\n\nBen was holding Camo's tank, looking calmer than anyone had a right to look. \"We should tell them,\" he said. \"About what happened. About how the pets helped find Leo.\"\n\n\"That's not really a trick.\"\n\n\"It's better than a trick. It's real.\"\n\nI thought about that. Ben was right. We didn't have costumes or routines or anything impressive. But we had a story. And maybe that was worth something.\n\n---\n\nWhen they called \"The Wrong Pet Club,\" we walked on stage together.\n\nThe judges sat at a long table with clipboards. The crowd was mostly parents trying to take pictures. The announcer looked bored, like he'd already seen too many pets today.\n\n\"And what category are you entering?\" he asked.\n\nI looked at Jenna. Jenna looked at Ben. Ben looked at Camo.\n\n\"Best Trick,\" I said.\n\nThe announcer raised an eyebrow. \"Alright. And what's your trick?\"\n\nThis was the part where we were supposed to do something. Speedy was supposed to sit or roll over or catch a frisbee. Camo was supposed to change colors. Duchess was supposed to exist visibly.\n\nInstead, I said: \"This morning, my dog found my brother.\"\n\nThe announcer blinked. \"Excuse me?\"\n\n\"My brother Leo was missing. He'd crawled under an old shed and gotten stuck in a hole. We couldn't find him. But Speedy—\" I put my hand on her head. \"Speedy found another entrance. She smelled her way to him. She stopped being slow and just... knew what to do.\"\n\nThe crowd had gone quiet. The judges were leaning forward.\n\n\"My chameleon helped too,\" Ben said. \"Kind of. He was there. And I had to crawl into a really dark, scary place to get Leo, and I was terrified, but Camo was on my chest the whole time. Just being brown. Just being Camo.\" He paused. \"Did you know chameleons can see in two directions at once? I think that helped me see better too. Maybe.\"\n\nIt didn't make total sense, but it was Ben, and nothing Ben said ever made total sense, and somehow that was fine.\n\nJenna stepped forward. \"And my cat Duchess—\"\n\nShe held up the carrier. Looked inside.\n\nEmpty.\n\n\"Oh no,\" she whispered. \"No, no, no, she was JUST there—\"\n\nA meow came from somewhere. Not from the carrier.\n\nWe all looked up.\n\nDuchess was sitting on the judges' table. Right in the middle. Right on top of a blue first-place ribbon. She was grooming her paw like she'd been there for hours.\n\n\"HOW—\" the announcer sputtered. \"When did—\"\n\n\"That's her thing,\" Jenna said weakly. \"She appears. And disappears. And appears somewhere else.\"\n\nOne of the judges reached out to touch Duchess. Duchess allowed it, regally, like she was granting a favor.\n\n\"She's real,\" the judge said, sounding surprised.\n\n\"I TOLD you she was real.\"\n\n\"She's beautiful. Why isn't she in the Most Photogenic category?\"\n\n\"Because she doesn't show up in PHOTOS,\" Jenna said, and then started laugh-crying, which is something I didn't know was possible until that moment.\n\n---\n\nWe didn't win Best Trick.\n\nWe didn't win any official category.\n\nBut at the end of the parade, after all the ribbons were given out and all the normal pets had done their normal tricks, the head judge stood up and cleared her throat.\n\n\"We have one more award to give out,\" she said. \"This one isn't on the program. We made it up just now, because we didn't have a category for what we saw today.\"\n\nShe looked right at us.\n\n\"The award for Most Surprising goes to... The Wrong Pet Club.\"\n\nThe crowd applauded—actual applause, not just polite parent-clapping. Someone whistled. Leo, standing with Mom and Dad at the edge of the square, was jumping up and down yelling \"THAT'S MY SISTER! AND HER WRONG DOG!\"\n\nThe judge handed us a ribbon. It was handmade, clearly created in the last five minutes, with \"MOST SURPRISING\" written in marker on a piece of cardstock.\n\nIt was the best ribbon I'd ever seen.\n\n---\n\nAfter the parade, we walked home together. The sun was setting, turning everything gold and orange. Speedy walked beside me, stopping to smell things—a mailbox, a leaf, a crack in the sidewalk—and for the first time, I didn't check my stopwatch.\n\nI just waited.\n\n\"Did you know dogs experience the world primarily through smell?\" Ben said. \"To them, every walk is like reading a newspaper. They're catching up on news.\"\n\n\"What kind of news?\"\n\n\"Who was here. What they ate. Where they went. It's all information, just in a different format.\"\n\nI watched Speedy sniff a fire hydrant. The same fire hydrant that had taken four minutes and twelve seconds on our first walk. She sniffed it for maybe thirty seconds this time, then moved on.\n\n\"She's getting faster,\" I said.\n\n\"Or you're getting slower,\" Ben replied.\n\nI thought about that. Maybe he was right.\n\nJenna was looking into Duchess's carrier again. Duchess was inside, visible, curled up and sleeping.\n\n\"She's been in here the whole walk,\" Jenna said, wonder in her voice. \"I keep checking and she keeps being there.\"\n\n\"Maybe she's tired from her big debut.\"\n\n\"Maybe.\" Jenna smiled. \"Or maybe she finally decided I was worth showing up for.\"\n\nShe looked back through her phone at her Instagram. All those photos of empty rooms. All those comments asking \"where's the cat?\" and \"is this a joke?\"\n\n\"I should post a new photo,\" she said. \"An actual photo. Of an actual cat.\"\n\n\"What would the caption be?\"\n\nJenna thought about it. Then she grinned. \"Finally.\"\n\n---\n\nWhen we got to my house, Leo was sitting on the porch, waiting.\n\nHe was holding his ribbon—a third-place ribbon for \"Best Smile,\" which Mrs. Park had entered him in without telling anyone. Apparently, his grin after finding the watch had been photographed by half the crowd.\n\n\"Maya!\" He jumped up. \"Did you win?\"\n\n\"We got Most Surprising.\"\n\n\"Is that good?\"\n\n\"I think it's the best we could have hoped for.\"\n\nHe nodded seriously, like this made perfect sense. Then he looked at Speedy.\n\n\"She found me,\" he said. \"Your slow dog found me.\"\n\n\"She did.\"\n\n\"So she's not really slow. She's just... careful. Right?\"\n\nI looked at Speedy. She was sniffing the porch, taking her time, processing information in a format I couldn't read.\n\n\"Yeah,\" I said. \"She's careful. She notices things other people miss. That's her superpower.\"\n\n\"I want a superpower like that.\"\n\n\"You already have one. You make maps. You notice hiding spots. You found Mrs. Park's watch when nobody else could.\"\n\nLeo beamed. It was the same smile that had won him third place.\n\n\"Can I join the Wrong Pet Club?\" he asked.\n\n\"You don't have a pet.\"\n\n\"I have you guys. And you're all wrong. In a good way.\"\n\nJenna laughed. Ben nodded. I looked at my little brother, who had spent weeks making maps of snails and squeaky gates and hiding spots, who had believed he could find a lost treasure when everyone else had given up.\n\n\"Yeah,\" I said. \"You can join.\"\n\n---\n\nThat night, I lay in bed and thought about the week.\n\nI thought about going to the shelter and losing Rocket by five minutes. I thought about meeting Ben in the parking lot with his brown chameleon, Jenna with her invisible cat. I thought about all those walks where Speedy stopped to smell things I couldn't see, all those times I'd been frustrated and impatient and convinced I'd gotten the wrong pet.\n\nMaybe I had gotten the wrong pet.\n\nBut maybe wrong was just a different kind of right.\n\nI grabbed my phone and opened the Smell Log. Fifty-three entries. Every stop, every duration, every confusing smell that made no sense.\n\nI looked at the data for a long time.\n\nThen I deleted it.\n\nNot because it didn't matter. It mattered. It was real. But I didn't need to measure Speedy anymore. I didn't need to track how slow she was or how many times she stopped or whether she was meeting some standard I'd invented.\n\nShe was my dog. And she was exactly the dog I needed.\n\n---\n\nThe next morning, I woke up early.\n\nSpeedy was lying by my bed, waiting. She did that every morning now—waited for me to wake up, then walked with me to the door, ready for whatever came next.\n\n\"Want to go for a walk?\" I asked.\n\nShe wagged her tail. Slowly, like always.\n\nWe went outside. The sun was just coming up. The street was quiet.\n\nSpeedy sniffed the air. Then she sniffed a crack in the sidewalk. Then she sniffed a mailbox, and a patch of grass, and a spot where something used to be but wasn't anymore.\n\nI didn't time it.\n\nI didn't count the stops.\n\nI just walked with her, slow and steady, noticing things I'd never noticed before. The way the light hit the trees. The sound of birds waking up. The feeling of morning, new and full of possibility.\n\nSpeedy stopped at the fire hydrant. The famous fire hydrant. The four-minute-twelve-second fire hydrant.\n\nShe sniffed it carefully, thoroughly, taking her time.\n\nAnd I waited.\n\nNot because I had to. Not because I was being patient.\n\nBecause I finally understood.\n\nSome things are worth slowing down for.\n\n---\n\n*The Wrong Pet Club*\n*Members: Maya, Ben, Jenna, Leo*\n*Pets: Speedy (slow), Camo (brown), Duchess (cryptid)*\n*Motto: \"Wrong is just different. Different is just us.\"*\n\nWe never made it official. We never had membership cards or meetings or a secret handshake.\n\nBut we had each other. And we had our pets.\n\nAnd that was exactly right.\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":5,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
